explanation:
1) UtAssert_True: The else-branch calls UtAssert_True(false,...). To decide whether any code after that call (notably the function return at the end) is unreachable you must know the semantics of UtAssert_True — specifically whether it can return normally or is defined as non‑returning (calls abort/exit/longjmp and/or annotated noreturn). If it does not return then the subsequent return statement (and any code after the call) would be unreachable.  

2) UtAssert_GetContext: This symbol appears in the static call graph and is typically part of the implementation of the UtAssert family. Its implementation/context may be needed to understand whether UtAssert_True (or related assertion machinery) transfers control (e.g., longjmp) or returns. Include UtAssert_GetContext so the asserting implementation can be fully analyzed for non‑returning behavior.
